[1] Snippets on country updates 14 Sep 2020
Date: Mon 14 Sep 2020
Source: Al Jazeera [abridged, edited]
https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/09/sees-record-single-day-jump-coronavirus-cases-live-news-200913231611514.html


- 22:54 GMT -- No deaths in Australia's Victoria for 1st time in 2 months
Victoria, the Australian state at the centre of Australia's latest coronavirus outbreak, has reported no deaths from COVID-19 for the 1st time in 2 months. The state confirmed 42 new cases in a 24-hour-period, compared with 35 the previous day.

[Transmission continues but at a much lower level than several weeks ago when some daily case reports were over 400. 9 Sep 2020 was the most recent day reporting more than 100 cases. - Mod.MPP]

- 22:40 GMT -- Brazil registers 15 155 new cases
Brazil registered 15 115 new cases of coronavirus, totalling 4 345 610, the health ministry said. Deaths rose by 381 to 131 625 according to ministry data.

[Daily case reports from Brazil have been much lower than previously. I suspect the numbers of the past few days have been the result of weekend artifact. On 11 Sep 2020, there were over 44 000 cases reported in the 24 hour period. - Mod.MPP]

- 20:40 GMT -- Turkey's virus deaths rise to levels not seen since May [2020]
Turkey's daily coronavirus deaths have topped its numbers from early May [2020], with 63 fatalities in the past 24 hours. The number of positive COVID-19 cases stands at nearly 293 000 since March [2020]. The death toll now is 7119, but experts say all numbers undercount the true impact of the coronavirus pandemic due to limited testing and missed mild cases, among other factors. Health Minister Fahrettin Koca tweeted that the rate of infections was not slowing and urged people to take precautions. Turkey eased restrictions like temporary weekend lockdowns at the end of May [2020] and reopened businesses and travel routes in June [2020].

[Turkey has been reporting 1500+ cases a day since mid-August 2020 (according to our files from Worldometer daily reports). An increase in mortality suggests an increase in cases and the possibility of undercapture/identification of cases is being discussed. - Mod.MPP]

- 20:25 GMT -- US officials: 500 000 counterfeit N95 masks seized in Chicago
About 500 000 counterfeit N95 respirator masks have been seized in Chicago by Customs and Border Protection officers, federal officials said. The shipment of masks from China was seized [10 Sep 2020] at O'Hare International Airport, according to the federal agency. It said the masks were headed to a company in Manalapan, New Jersey. The masks are used to prevent the spread of the COVID-19 virus. "These masks did not meet the safety standards outlined by the CDC, which puts the public at risk, jeopardizing the health and well-being of everyone," said Shane Campbell, port director for the Chicago area.

[The N95 respirator masks are the masks reserved for front-line workers with probable daily exposures to infected individuals. - Mod.MPP]

- 19:30 GMT -- Jordan to close mosques, restaurants, and schools for 2 weeks
Mosques, restaurants, street markets, and most schools will be closed for 2 weeks starting Thursday [17 Sep 2020] in Jordan, amid an "unprecedented" increase in coronavirus infections and deaths in the kingdom. These measures will help to avoid a total lockdown, government spokesman Amjad al-Adaileh said. In recent days, Jordan has reported more than 200 cases and several deaths every day, a record high it has avoided earlier in the year due to a tight lockdown. "Despite previous warnings, we have seen recklessness and complacency that unfortunately led to dozens of cases in different provinces across the kingdom. So, concerned authorities will take very strict measures against those who violate" the rules, al-Adaileh said in a televised address.

[A common observation when restrictions are lifted. - Mod.MPP]

- 19:00 GMT -- Canada's Trudeau worried about uptick in virus cases
Prime Minister Justin Trudeau has warned that Canada was "not out of the woods" with the coronavirus, urging citizens to be vigilant as more than 1300 cases were recorded over the weekend [12-13 Sep 2020] -- a level not seen since early summer. "One of the things we're seeing is, with numbers rising across the country, we are not out of the woods," Trudeau told a press conference in Ottawa. He said the resumption of classes and the reopening of the Canadian economy, meaning more people are back to work, had led to an increase in case numbers.

[It is a common observation: lift restrictions, cases increase. - Mod.MPP]

- 18:30 GMT -- UAE announces emergency approval for use of COVID-19 vaccine
The United Arab Emirates has granted emergency approval for use of a coronavirus vaccine, 6 weeks after human trials in the country started. A phase III trial of a COVID-19 inactivated vaccine developed by Chinese state-owned pharmaceutical company Sinopham began in the UAE in July [2020] and is yet to be completed. "The vaccine will be available to our 1st line of defense heroes who are at the highest risk of contracting the virus," said the National Emergency Crisis and Disaster Management Authority in a tweet.

[We await published results on this candidate vaccine. - Mod.MPP]

- 18:00 GMT -- Testing positive: half of Argentina's coronavirus checks yield infection
Argentina's coronavirus "positive rate," the number of daily infections to the number of tests carried out, has topped 50 percent, underscoring how much work the South American country has to do to bring the virus under control. Health ministry data showed the country carried out 17 955 tests the day before, when it recorded 9056 confirmed COVID-19 cases. That indicates a positive rate of 50.4 percent, one of the highest in the world. The country, which has been trying to open its hard-hit economy, has a total of 555 537 confirmed cases, the 10th-highest case load in the world, with 11 412 fatalities.

[A 50% positivity rate is indicative of reduced testing, prioritizing most likely symptomatic cases. - Mod.MPP]

- 17:30 GMT -- Egypt to allow wedding ceremonies, cultural events in open-air venues
Egypt will allow wedding ceremonies and cultural events to be held in open-air venues from [21 Sep 2020], after months of banning them in an attempt to contain the spread of the coronavirus, the cabinet said. Open-air weddings would be allowed in tourist and hotel facilities that obtained health safety certificates, with a maximum of 300 invitees, it added in a statement. These facilities would also be able to host meetings and conferences with not more than 150 participants, it said. Cultural exhibitions, including book fairs, would be allowed in open-air venues with a maximum attendance of 50 percent of capacity, the statement said.

[Good luck! - Mod.MPP]

- 17:00 GMT -- UK reports 2621 new cases of COVID-19
A total of 2621 new positive cases were recorded across the United Kingdom, Public Health England said. The new cases take the cumulative total number of cases to 371 125. Public Health England also said 9 new deaths had been reported, taking the UK total since the start of the pandemic to 41 637.

[Daily newly confirmed cases have been ranging in the 2500-3500 range since 6 Sep 2020, having been below 2000 since 24 May 2020 (data from Worldometer files we maintain). - Mod.MPP]

- 16:35 GMT -- World dangerously unprepared for next pandemic: monitor
In a new report, the Global Preparedness Monitoring Board (GPMB), an independent body created by the World Health Organization and the World Bank, decried that the coronavirus pandemic had revealed how little the world had focused on preparing for such disasters, despite ample warnings that large disease outbreaks were inevitable. "The COVID-19 pandemic is providing a harsh test of the world's preparedness," the report said, concluding that little progress had been made on any of the actions it had called for in its initial report last year [2020] before COVID-19 struck. "Failure to learn the lessons of COVID-19 or to act on them with the necessary resources and commitment will mean that the next pandemic, which is sure to come, will be even more damaging," it warned.

[How sadly true these observations are. - Mod.MPP]

- 15:45 GMT -- Bayern Munich offers free virus tests to fans
German football club Bayern Munich has offered free coronavirus tests to fans with tickets for next week's Super Cup in Hungary. The Hungarian authorities require fans arriving for the traditional European season opener to have a certified negative result from a recent test for the virus before they are allowed into the country. The club says 3000 Bayern fans with tickets for the game can be tested on [21 and 22 Sep 2020] at a parking lot next to the stadium.

[The game will be on 24 Sep 2020, and the stadium will be open to 30% capacity -- approximately 20 165 spectators. (https://www.bavarianfootballworks.com/2020/8/25/21401200/uefa-supercup-2020-bayern-munich-sevilla-fans-in-the-stadium-budapest-puskas-arena)

- 15:15 GMT -- Russia completes volunteer recruitment for COVID-19 vaccine trial
Russia has recruited sufficient participants for its large-scale COVID-19 vaccine trial, known as a phase III trial, the head of Russia's sovereign wealth fund, which is backing the vaccine, said. "In just 2 weeks, 55 000 volunteers have already been recruited in Moscow," Kirill Dmitriev, head of the Russian Direct Investment Fund Said. Russia began recruiting for what was billed as a 40 000-strong phase III trial on [26 Aug 2020]. Initial results are expected in October or November this year [2020], officials have said.

[See COVID-19 update (390): Russia vaccine trial, vaping risk factor, WHO, global 20200905.7748995 for the link and abstract of the Russian vaccine phase II results. - Mod.MPP]

- 14:50 GMT -- At least 1.7 million jobs lost in Kenya due to coronavirus fallout
The Kenya National Bureau of Statistics estimated that around 1.7 million people have been made redundant due to the outbreak during this time. According to the Federation of Kenya Employers (FKE), a total of 604 firms in Kenya have sent workers home due to the coronavirus fallout. Speaking to Kenya's local daily the Nation, the FKE said at least 33 jobs were lost in every modern sector company between March and August 2020. "The worst is yet to come as workers continue to grapple with the impact of the pandemic, especially the consequences of the abrupt shutting down of economic activities," Jacqueline Mugo, the FKE executive director, said.

[Serious economic hardships related to the pandemic are impacting many countries. - Mod.MPP]

- 14:20 GMT -- Romania reopens schools under strict rules as coronavirus cases rise
Romania has reopened more than 17 000 schools for 2.8 million children after a 6-month closure to fight the coronavirus outbreak, ordering pupils to wear face masks as infections rise. With 104 000 cases, and new infections jumping above 1000 a day since July [2020], millions of teachers, students, and parents face a tough challenge to adapt after months of online teaching at home. President Klaus Iohannis urged students "to become super-heroes who wear the mask, wash hands, and listen to their teachers, protect parents and grandparents, the most exposed to the danger of getting sick."

[No further information on how schools are opening, if 100% daily attendance or if reduced daily attendance. - Mod.MPP]

- 10:45 GMT -- Eli Lilly's rheumatoid arthritis drug helps recovery in COVID-19 patients
Eli Lilly and Co said its rheumatoid arthritis drug Olumiant [baricitinib] helped reduce the time taken to recover from COVID-19 in hospitalized patients in a clinical trial. The US drugmaker said the drug, in combination with Gilead Sciences Inc's remdesivir, met the main goal of shortening recovery when compared to remdesivir alone.

[Discussion of the results from Eli Lily is available at https://www.politico.com/news/2020/09/14/eli-lilly-coronavirus-anti-inflammatory-drug-414478. The results have not been published yet, nor is a pre-peer review publication available. According to the company (and confirmed by NIAID), the combination of baricitinib with remdesivir reduced recovery time by one day. - Mod.MPP]

- 09:28 GMT -- Italy's schools finally reopen after 6-month closure
After a 6-month shutdown, the longest in Europe, Italy reopened most of its schools, testing the organisational skills of the government, the nerves of teachers, and the self-control of excited students. Schools in 13 of the country's 20 regions cautiously resumed face-to-face lessons, calling back 5.6 million students to their desks. The remaining 7 regions have decided to delay for another week. Battling to halt the spread of coronavirus, the government shut the nation's schools in early March [2020]. Efforts to make classrooms safe again and limit the possibility of fresh contagion have been mired in controversy. "At the beginning, there are going to be problems," Prime Minister Giuseppe Conte said. In Italy, about 35 500 people have died of COVID-19, the largest death toll in the European Union, and the number of new cases has picked up recently raising fears of a 2nd wave.

[Following the comparative 7-day averages for this week and 8-18 days preceding this past week, over the weekend the daily case count changes for Italy have markedly decreased (?weekend artifact influencing these figures); there is an increase of 4.4% in newly confirmed cases and an increase of 1.4% in daily reported deaths. On Fri 11 Sep 2020, the comparative 7 day average changes were an 8.6% increase in newly confirmed cases and a 71.7% increase in daily reported deaths (data from spreadsheets we maintain on daily reports from the Italian MOH http://www.salute.gov.it/portale/nuovocoronavirus/dettaglioContenutiNuovoCoronavirus.jsp?lingua=italiano&id=5351&area=nuovoCoronavirus&menu=vuoto). - Mod.MPP]

- 08:47 GMT -- Indonesia reports 3141 new infections, 118 deaths
Indonesia reported 3141 new coronavirus cases, taking the total number of cases in the Southeast Asian country to 221 523, data from the country's COVID-19 task force showed. The data added 118 new deaths, taking the total to 8841, the highest death toll in South East Asia.

[Indonesia has been reporting over 3000 newly confirmed cases daily since 2 Sep 2020. The outbreak continues and it ranks 2nd in the South East Asia region, just behind India for daily newly confirmed cases. - Mod.MPP]

- 08:46 GMT -- Philippines reports another record spike in daily coronavirus deaths
The Philippines reported a record daily increase in new coronavirus deaths for the 2nd time in 3 days, adding 259 more fatalities to bring the total to 4630. In a bulletin, the health ministry said the Southeast Asian country also recorded 4699 newly-confirmed cases, taking its total infections to 265 888, the highest in the region.

[The Philippines has been the dominant country in the Western Pacific region with respect to ongoing transmission of the SARS-CoV-2. Our daily WHO reports highlight this (except on Mondays...). - Mod.MPP]

- 07:28 GMT -- Crowded Marseille soccer celebrations condemned by French minister
French interior minister Gerald Darmanin criticised Olympique Marseille's (OM) fans for celebrating en masse on the streets of the city after Marseille beat Paris Saint Germain (PSG), given the risks from the COVID-19 virus in France. "One can only condemn the images that we are seeing," Darmanin told LCI television when shown TV footage of hordes of Marseille supporters partying after the win in close proximity to one another, with many not wearing masks. Last week [week of 7 Sep 2020], French Prime Minister Jean Castex singled out Marseille and Bordeaux as among the mainland French cities hardest hit by the resurgence of the COVID virus in France. Marseille's hospitals have also been put back on a crisis footing as the virus has started to spread again in France, which has the world's 7th-highest COVID-19 death toll.

[With the current ongoing upsurge in SARS-CoV-2 transmission in Marseille, the street partying may be like adding fuel to a fire and further increase the virus transmission. Time will tell. - Mod.MPP]

- 06:43 GMT -- Japan will not play again in 2020 due to COVID-19 - JRFU
Japan's national rugby union team will not play again this year [2020] because of safety fears related to the COVID-19 pandemic, the Japanese Rugby Football Union (JRFU) said. Japan, who had games against England and Wales cancelled earlier this year [2020] due to the novel coronavirus outbreak, were due to play Scotland and Ireland in November [2020].

[Sports are on the list of collateral damages during the pandemic. - Mod.MPP]

- 06:18 GMT -- Czech Republic's daily count of cases drops below 1000 after 5 days
The Czech Republic recorded 792 new coronavirus cases on Sunday [13 Sep 2020], a drop after 5 consecutive days with more than 1000 cases each, Health Ministry's data showed. The ministry has not yet updated the daily number of tests. There are usually fewer tests done at weekends. The overall number of confirmed cases rose to 36 188 in the country of 10.7 million.

[Most likely weekend artifact as according to today's (14 Sep 2020) Worldometer report there were over 1000 cases reported in the past 24 hours (check https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/SEPT14DATASET_1600139249.pdf for today's report and https://promedmail.org/wp-content/uploads/world-pdf/SEPT14WORLD7_1600139301.pdf for the past 7 days' reports). - Mod.MPP]

- 06:15 GMT -- October, November [2020] to be 'tougher' with more coronavirus deaths: WHO Europe
The World Health Organization expects Europe to see a rise in the daily number of COVID-19 deaths in October and November, the head of the body's European branch told AFP news agency. "It's going to get tougher. In October, November [2020], we are going to see more mortality," WHO Europe director Hans Kluge said, as the continent currently experiences a surge of cases though the number of deaths has remained relatively stable.

[As the weather cools off, more indoor time with other people challenging social distancing, indoor restaurant dining, with face masks removed for eating and drinking... - Mod.MPP]

- 05:45 GMT -- India reports 92 071 new coronavirus cases; deaths near 80 000
India's health ministry reported on Monday [14 Sep 2020] at least 92 071 new cases of the coronavirus, taking total cases to 4.85 million. The figure is slightly lower than the more than 94 000 cases reported on Sunday [13 Sep 2020], but India continues to report cases over 90 000 for days. More than 1100 deaths were also reported, taking the death toll to almost 80 000.

[India has been reporting more than 90 000 new cases on a daily basis since 5 Sep 2020. Today's Worldometer report has 81 000+ newly confirmed cases. 1st time below 90 000 cases since 5 Sep 2020. The reported numbers above are higher than reported on the Worldometer website... - Mod.MPP]

- 05:18 GMT -- Ethnic groups in Myanmar's Rakhine fear army more than COVID-19
Amid the coronavirus virus pandemic, which has infected almost 3000 people in Myanmar, ethnic groups in Rakhine state are fearing the miliary onslaught more than the spread of the disease. According to reports obtained by Al Jazeera, more than 100 houses in 2 villages had been razed, forcing as many as 8000 villages to flee their homes. An estimated 3 million people of Rakhine are caught in the intensifying armed conflict between the military -- known as the Tatmadaw -- and the Arakan Army (AA), an ethnic armed group.

[Civil unrest has not disappeared during the pandemic. - Mod.MPP]

- 05:00 GMT -- Doctors in Indonesia fight spread of fake news on COVID-19
The Doctors Without Borders (also known as MSF) has called on the Indonesian government to step up education regarding the spread of the coronavirus in the country, saying that the spread of rumours and fake news is creating "panic" in many communities. "We needed to help them find a way to educate and inform the community quickly and on a large scale. Fear can be just as harmful as COVID-19," said Dr Dirna Mayasari, the MSF deputy medical coordinator in Indonesia. MSF said that in one community in South Jakarta, for example, villagers "were so confused" after receiving inaccurate information, some of which are "defined as fake news" regarding the spread of the deadly disease.

[Fake news is a serious problem, especially when trying to implement control measures and give solid advice to the population on how to prevent infections. - Mod.MPP]

- 04:40 GMT -- 10 new COVID-19 cases reported in China
China's National Health Commission has reported 10 new coronavirus cases, bringing the country's confirmed cases to 85 194. In a statement on Monday [14 Sep 2020], the commission also said that there were no additional fatalities reported keeping the death toll unchanged at over 4600. China also reported 39 new asymptomatic cases, which the government does not include in its total count.

[The most recent locally acquired case in China was reported on 15 Aug 2020. Since then, all reported cases have been classified as imported cases. In the most recent daily report from the National Health Commission, there have been a total of 2653 imported cases confirmed (this does not include those that were asymptomatic throughout their documented infection). http://www.nhc.gov.cn/xcs/yqtb/202009/a2f6fc89b8c545ecb806a86b6bc5437a.shtml. - Mod.MPP

- 04:10 GMT -- Coronavirus panel slams failure to head warnings
The Global Preparedness Monitoring Board, a panel reviewing the response of the coronavirus pandemic, has denounced the collective failure by political leaders that led to the current "disorder". "Financial and political investments in preparedness have been insufficient, and we are all paying the price," according to the report prepared by the panel organised by the World Bank and the World Health Organization. "It is not as if the world has lacked the opportunity to take these steps," it added. "There have been numerous calls for action... over the last decade, yet none has generated the changes needed."

[As stated above, unfortunately true... - Mod.MPP]

- 03:35 GMT -- Doctors oppose easing of social-distancing rules in the Philippines
Doctors in the Philippines have expressed opposition to the government's plan to easing physical distancing regulations in the country, saying it is too early to relax the rules. In an online forum on Monday [14 Sep 2020], Dr Antonio Dans, a leading expert on the country's university healthcare law, said that the department of transportation should not change its rule of one metre between passengers, as it could lead to more transmission. The government plans to gradually reduce social distancing rules on public transportation to just half a metre [almost 2 ft] on [28 Sep 2020] and 0.3 meters [1 ft] on [12 Oct 2020] to increase the capacity of trains and buses. The country has over 261 000 cases and at least 4371 deaths due to the pandemic.

[Listen to the public health experts... - Mod.MPP]

- 03:05 GMT -- Germany's confirmed coronavirus cases rise by 927 to 260 355
Germany's monitor for infectious diseases has reported that the country's COVID-19 cases have gone up by 927 to 260 355. The Robert Koch Institute (RKI) also reported on Monday [14 Sep 2020] that the death toll rose by one to 9350.

[According to today's (14 Sep 2020) Worldometer report, in the past 24 hours there have been over 1900 newly confirmed cases, suggesting the earlier reports were still showing weekend artifacts in reporting as case reports prior to the weekend were also above 1000. - Mod.MPP]

- 02:50 GMT -- Israel to reinstate lockdown
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has announced that the country will reinstate a strict new countrywide lockdown this week amid a resurgence of COVID-19 cases. Starting on Friday [18 Sep 2020], schools, restaurants, malls, and hotels among other businesses will shut down and restrictions on movement will be imposed. The lockdown is expected to last at least 3 weeks, when measures may be eased depending on the rate of increase of cases and fatalities. Israel has over 155 000 cases and around 1100 deaths.

[The lockdown will coincide with the beginning of the high holiday period (Rosh Hoshana & Yom Kippur) and will extend into the Sukkot holiday (harvest celebration). - Mod.MPP]

- 02:01 GMT -- Saudi to lift international restrictions Tuesday [15 Sep 2020]
Saudi Arabia's interior ministry has announced that it will partially lift restrictions on international flights beginning on Tuesday [15 Sep 2020], 6 months after travel curbs were imposed due to the pandemic. After [1 Jan 2021], Saudi Arabia will also end all restrictions on air, land, and sea transport for Saudi citizens, but the exact date will be announced later in December [2020]. According to the Saudi Press Agency, non- Saudi residents with valid travel documents can enter Saudi as long as they are free of the virus.

[Saudi Arabia will be watched closely to see if there is an impact of opening up travel. - Mod.MPP]

- 01:42 GMT -- New Zealand to lift most of coronavirus curbs on [21 Sep 2020]
New Zealand Prime Minister Jacinda Ardern announced on Monday [14 Sep 2020] that coronavirus restrictions across the country will be lifted on [21 Sep 2020], except in its biggest city of Auckland which is the epicentre of a 2nd wave of infections. Ardern said Auckland's restrictions would be reviewed next week.

[The last day there were more than 10 newly confirmed cases reported was 31 Aug 2020. In the past week, there have been less than 5 cases per day. - Mod.MPP]

- 01:25 GMT -- Trump indoor rally plan prompts virus warning
US President Donald Trump was due to hold his 1st fully indoor rally in months in the state of Nevada, but authorities warned the gathering could violate coronavirus restrictions on crowd sizes. Indoor rallies during the pandemic have proven problematic for Trump, who was heavily criticised after one in June [2020] that was later linked to a spike in virus cases. Plans for the rally in the Nevada city of Henderson on Sunday [13 Sep 2020] drew a rebuke from local authorities who noted events with more than 50 people are not allowed due to the coronavirus, according to Reuters news agency.

[No comment. - Mod.MPP]

- 01:02 GMT -- South Korea reports decline in new cases with 109 testing positive
South Korea's coronavirus monitoring agency reported on Monday [14 Sep 2020] at least 109 COVID-19 cases -- the 12th straight day that infections stayed below 200. Yonhap quoted the Korea Disease Control and Prevention Agency as saying that of the new cases reported, 98 were of domestic origin, with the overall total hitting 22 285. 5 more deaths were also reported, compared to 3 on Sunday [14 Sep 2020], raising the death toll to 363.

[The most recent report from 15 Sep 2020 at 00.00hrs Korean time, notes there were 106 newly confirmed cases. It has been 33 days that daily reported newly confirmed cases have been above 100. The death toll has been increasing in the past 2-3 weeks related to these increased clusters. - Mod.MPP]

- 00:45 GMT -- Mexico's coronavirus deaths near 71 000
Mexico's health ministry has reported 4408 new coronavirus cases and 217 additional deaths, bringing the total number of infections to 668 381 and the death toll to 70 821 deaths. The government has said the real number of infected people is likely higher than the confirmed cases, and the country has also reported over 120 000 in excess deaths in recent months.

[Mexico has been in the top 20 countries vis-à-vis daily newly confirmed cases for several months now and is the 9th highest country in terms of cumulative case counts. The figures on excess deaths are sobering as they include COVID-19 directly related deaths (those who die at home) and indirectly related (those who die of other causes that weren't followed by the health sector). - Mod.MPP]

- 00:10 GMT -- Australia's Victoria sees lowest rise in COVID-19 cases
Victoria, the 2nd-most populous state in Australia and the centre of the country's coronavirus outbreak, has reported its lowest number of new cases in 3 months. The state reported 35 new cases on Monday [14 Sep 2020], and 7 deaths. Melbourne has begun to ease some of the restrictions imposed to curb the spread of COVID-19 disease. Residents are now allowed to spend an additional 2 hours outside every day, and the city's controversial overnight curfew has been shortened by 1 hour.

[Hopefully, this easing of restrictions won't immediately be followed by increases in reported cases. - Mod.MPP]

- 00:05 GMT -- WHO reports record one-day increase in cases, up over 307 000
The World Health Organization has reported another record-breaking number of coronavirus cases, worldwide with at least 307 930 cases in just one day. The previous record reported by WHO was 306 857 on [6 Sep 2020]. India, the United States, and Brazil posted the highest number of cases, with India reporting over 94 300 cases on Sunday [13 Sep 2020]. Europe has also seen a resurgence of cases.

[At this rate of reporting there are 1 million newly confirmed cases ever 3.3 days. - Mod.MPP]

- 00:01 GMT -- Greece reports 207 new COVID-19 cases as it prepares to reopen schools
Greek health authorities have reported 207 new coronavirus cases including 29 infections from abroad, with 3 more fatalities, as the country prepares to reopen its schools on Monday [14 Sep 2020]. The total cases now stand at 13 240 and 305 deaths. Of the total number of cases, about 3/4 were recorded in August [2020], with a median age of 39. Meanwhile, among the fatalities, the average age is 78.

[Byline: Ted Regencia, Farah Najjar, Linah Alsaafin]

